context.text:
According to Leibnitz's Rule [12], for where,

14)
\$\varphi(x)\$ is a continuous function which depends on the parameter \$x\$, and has a continuous derivative for \$x_{1}\leq x\leq x_{2}\$;

15)
\$a\$, \$x_{1}\$, \$x_{2}\$, is a constant respectively;

16)
\$f_{1}(x,u)\$, and \$\partial f_{1}/\partial x\$ are also continuous in both \$x\$, and \$u\$ in some region of the \$xu\$ plane including \$a\leq u\leq\varphi(x)\$, and \$x_{1}\leq x\leq x_{2}\$;

and, for an improper integral, let \$f_{2}(x,u)\$ also satisfy the conditions stated above, and \$\int_{\varphi(x)}^{\infty} (\partial f_{2}/\partial x)du\$ converges uniformly in \$x_{1}\leq x\leq x_{2}\$, if \$f_{1}(x, \varphi(x))=f_{2}(x, \varphi(x))\$, then we have for \$x_{1}\leq x\leq x_{2}\$.
